113 - Never generate action that didn't occur\n+114 \n+115 **Language register:**\n+116 - No corporate slogans or filler phrases\n+117 - No \"pipe dream\" as a closer — use \"Nice dream. But impractical.\" or equivalent\n+118 - Compressed sentences over long-winded explanations\n+119 - Closer should land clean, not promotional\n+120 \n+121 **Post vs Image priority:**\n+122 - Post-first when the hook is the copy itself\n+123 - Image-first when the visual metaphor carries the weight\n+124 - Don't default to image search — wait for the user's decision\n+125 \n+126 **Grammarly:**\n+127 - Colored underlines = Grammarly tool artifact, NOT intentional author emphasis\n+128 - Never read underlines as deliberate writing choices\n+129 \n+130 **Critical for agent training:** These rules represent Tiny's distinct voice. They should be encoded into the Nava agent's system prompt as hard constraints, not suggestions. When in doubt, apply these over general LinkedIn best practices.\n  89 - Wants pushback over agreeability during concept development.\n  90 - Strong preference for concept pressure-testing before drafting.\n  91 - LinkedIn workflow preference: concept discussion -> decide image-first/post-first -> finalize LinkedIn post -> derive X -> optional channels.\n  92 - Visual preference: realistic, striking images; caption must complement image (not restate it).\n     ...","firstChangedLine":89},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773958543983}}
