{"type":"message","id":"502217aa","parentId":"9e61183f","timestamp":"2026-03-19T23:46:19.679Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_a4ebd3fd-ef16-4c04-b14f-74cc12dfa583","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 - <<'PY'\nimport base64, json, urllib.request\nimg_path = \"~/.openclaw/media/browser/4f7f0e46-3391-4f7d-9d40-76e4b5a69dba.png\"\nimg_path = img_path.replace(\"~\", \"/home/tiny4lurv\")\nwith open(img_path, \"rb\") as f:\n    img_b64 = base64.b64encode(f.read()).decode()\npayload = {\"model\": \"gemma3:27b-cloud\", \"messages\":[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Describe this LinkedIn profile page in detail. What name appears? What is the headline? List any post content you can read.\", \"images\": [img_b64]}], \"stream\": False}\nreq = urllib.request.Request(\"http://localhost:11434/api/chat\", data=json.dumps(payload).encode(), headers={\"Content-Type\": \"application/json\"}, method=\"POST\")\nwith urllib.request.urlopen(req, timeout=60) as r:\n    print(json.loads(r.read())[\"message\"][\"content\"])\nPY","timeout":90}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.5:cloud","usage":{"input":53949,"output":283,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":54232,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1773963979679}}
{"type":"message","id":"42737164","parentId":"502217aa","timestamp":"2026-03-19T23:46:28.846Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_a4ebd3fd-ef16-4c04-b14f-74cc12dfa583","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here's a detailed description of the LinkedIn profile page as seen in the image:\n\n**Name:** Yosef Boston\n\n**Headline:** Chief Operating Officer & Co-Founder at Nava Healthcare Recruitment. Managing Director at Boston Management & Consulting.\n\n**Profile Summary (Left Side of Screen):**\n\n*   States his roles as Chief Operating Officer & Co-Founder at Nava Healthcare Recruitment and Managing Director at Boston Management & Consulting.\n*   Followers: 6,088\n*   A \"Message\" button is visible.\n\n**Post Content (Center of Screen):**\n\nThe post appears to have been published 2 months ago (2mo). Here's the full text, as readable from the image:\n\n\"Walk into any healthcare facility breakdown, and the narrative is the same: “if administration just took the $100/hr they pay the agency and gave it to us, we wouldn’t be short-staffed.”\n\nTo the staff, it looks like indifference, or even callousness. It feels demoralizing to watch a stranger get paid double while your loyalty is ignored (even if they are splitting that hourly with an agency).\n\nBut having sat in the executive chair, I know what it looks like from the other side: The Tenure Trap.\n\nWhen you are looking at the P&L, you are often staring at a brutal choice:\n\n1.  Hire 10 Agency Nurses at a premium (Variable Cost).\n2.  Raise the base rate to attract 10 Staff Nurses (Fixed Cost).\n\nThe math is unforgiving. Because of union step-scales or rigid pay bands, raising the Start Rate for those 10 new hires often legally triggers a pay reset for hundreds of existing clinicians.\n\nI’ve seen the models where the cost of the agency contract was $2M, but the cost of the system-wide pay reset was $15M.\n\nAdministrators don’t sign that agency contract because they don’t value agency profits—they sign it to avoid a far larger, systemic expense.\"\n\n**Right Side of Screen**\n*LinkedIn branding and a \"Your job search powered by your network\" with a button to explore jobs.\n* Links to About, Accessibility, Help Center, Privacy & Terms, Ad Choices, Advertising, Business Services, Get the LinkedIn App\n* Copyright information: LinkedIn Corporation © 2026\n\n**Bottom of the screen:**\n*   There are two notification icons visible, one indicating a message from \"Harvard Business...\" and the other a generic \"Messaging 1\".\n\nLet me know if you'd like any specific part of the profile described in more detail!"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":9160,"aggregated":"Here's a detailed description of the LinkedIn profile page as seen in the image:\n\n**Name:** Yosef Boston\n\n**Headline:** Chief Operating Officer & Co-Founder at Nava Healthcare Recruitment. Managing Director at Boston Management & Consulting.\n\n**Profile Summary (Left Side of Screen):**\n\n*   States his roles as Chief Operating Officer & Co-Founder at Nava Healthcare Recruitment and Managing Director at Boston Management & Consulting.\n*   Followers: 6,088\n*   A \"Message\" button is visible.\n\n**Post Content (Center of Screen):**\n\nThe post appears to have been published 2 months ago (2mo). Here's the full text, as readable from the image:\n\n\"Walk into any healthcare facility breakdown, and the narrative is the same: “if administration just took the $100/hr they pay the agency and gave it to us, we wouldn’t be short-staffed.”\n\nTo the staff, it looks like indifference, or even callousness. It feels demoralizing to watch a stranger get paid double while your loyalty is ignored (even if they are splitting that hourly with an agency).\n\nBut having sat in the executive chair, I know what it looks like from the other side: The Tenure Trap.\n\nWhen you are looking at the P&L, you are often staring at a brutal choice:\n\n1.  Hire 10 Agency Nurses at a premium (Variable Cost).\n2.  Raise the base rate to attract 10 Staff Nurses (Fixed Cost).\n\nThe math is unforgiving. Because of union step-scales or rigid pay bands, raising the Start Rate for those 10 new hires often legally triggers a pay reset for hundreds of existing clinicians.\n\nI’ve seen the models where the cost of the agency contract was $2M, but the cost of the system-wide pay reset was $15M.\n\nAdministrators don’t sign that agency contract because they don’t value agency profits—they sign it to avoid a far larger, systemic expense.\"\n\n**Right Side of Screen**\n*LinkedIn branding and a \"Your job search powered by your network\" with a button to explore jobs.\n* Links to About, Accessibility, Help Center, Privacy & Terms, Ad Choices, Advertising, Business Services, Get the LinkedIn App\n* Copyright information: LinkedIn Corporation © 2026\n\n**Bottom of the screen:**\n*   There are two notification icons visible, one indicating a message from \"Harvard Business...\" and the other a generic \"Messaging 1\".\n\nLet me know if you'd like any specific part of the profile described in more detail!","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773963988844}}
