{"type":"message","id":"b939a468","parentId":"235f90b1","timestamp":"2026-03-20T00:03:48.129Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_2abe0c3d-5c7a-43ab-9468-7ae52fddbb82","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"We saved a client over $𝟲𝟬,𝟬𝟬𝟬 recently. Not through a sales call or getting them a new deal. We did it by making a phone call they didn't know they needed. We were doing a routine check-in with a new star clinician when she told us, \"I love the job, but I’m resigning next Thursday\". The facility had no idea; they were about to be blindsided. The reason? Her son’s high school graduation was at 5:00 PM. She needed to leave her shift 2 hours early. The facility’s handbook stated clearly: \"New employees don't qualify for PTO\". And so, she had tried to solve it the right way, but she hit a wall of necessary guardrails from her immediate superiors: &nbsp;&nbsp;1. 𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗦𝘁𝗮𝗳𝗳 𝗗𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗹𝗼𝗽𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗖𝗼𝗼𝗿𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗮𝘁𝗼𝗿 (𝗦𝗗𝗖): Denied the request. Her unit was already short-staffed. If she made an exception for the \"new hire,\" that would raise the eyebrows of tenured staff. She wasn't being mean; she was protecting her floor and avoiding a personal infraction. &nbsp;&nbsp;2. 𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗨𝗻𝗶𝘁 𝗠𝗮𝗻𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗿: Denied the request. The first question the unit manager asked was, “What did the SDC say?” The floor leader didn’t want to undermine the SDC’s authority and favor a new hire on a policy that is black and white. 𝙀𝙫𝙚𝙧𝙮𝙤𝙣𝙚 𝙖𝙘𝙩𝙚𝙙 𝙧𝙖𝙩𝙞𝙤𝙣𝙖𝙡𝙡𝙮. 𝘼𝙣𝙙 𝙞𝙩 𝙬𝙖𝙨 𝙖𝙗𝙤𝙪𝙩 𝙩𝙤 𝙘𝙤𝙨𝙩 𝙩𝙝𝙚 𝙛𝙖𝙘𝙞𝙡𝙞𝙩𝙮 𝙖 𝙛𝙤𝙧𝙩𝙪𝙣𝙚. But we caught wind of the situation, intervened and called the CFO directly. I didn't need to lecture him on retention economics. The moment I explained the impasse, that a policy technicality was forcing a resignation, he saw the math"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":86,"aggregated":"We saved a client over $𝟲𝟬,𝟬𝟬𝟬 recently. Not through a sales call or getting them a new deal. We did it by making a phone call they didn't know they needed. We were doing a routine check-in with a new star clinician when she told us, \"I love the job, but I’m resigning next Thursday\". The facility had no idea; they were about to be blindsided. The reason? Her son’s high school graduation was at 5:00 PM. She needed to leave her shift 2 hours early. The facility’s handbook stated clearly: \"New employees don't qualify for PTO\". And so, she had tried to solve it the right way, but she hit a wall of necessary guardrails from her immediate superiors: &nbsp;&nbsp;1. 𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗦𝘁𝗮𝗳𝗳 𝗗𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗹𝗼𝗽𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗖𝗼𝗼𝗿𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗮𝘁𝗼𝗿 (𝗦𝗗𝗖): Denied the request. Her unit was already short-staffed. If she made an exception for the \"new hire,\" that would raise the eyebrows of tenured staff. She wasn't being mean; she was protecting her floor and avoiding a personal infraction. &nbsp;&nbsp;2. 𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗨𝗻𝗶𝘁 𝗠𝗮𝗻𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗿: Denied the request. The first question the unit manager asked was, “What did the SDC say?” The floor leader didn’t want to undermine the SDC’s authority and favor a new hire on a policy that is black and white. 𝙀𝙫𝙚𝙧𝙮𝙤𝙣𝙚 𝙖𝙘𝙩𝙚𝙙 𝙧𝙖𝙩𝙞𝙤𝙣𝙖𝙡𝙡𝙮. 𝘼𝙣𝙙 𝙞𝙩 𝙬𝙖𝙨 𝙖𝙗𝙤𝙪𝙩 𝙩𝙤 𝙘𝙤𝙨𝙩 𝙩𝙝𝙚 𝙛𝙖𝙘𝙞𝙡𝙞𝙩𝙮 𝙖 𝙛𝙤𝙧𝙩𝙪𝙣𝙚. But we caught wind of the situation, intervened and called the CFO directly. I didn't need to lecture him on retention economics. The moment I explained the impasse, that a policy technicality was forcing a resignation, he saw the math","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773965028126}}
